Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas said Thursday at a session of the UN General Assembly that he would break any agreements reached with Israel if the country’s future government tries to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu’s pledge to annex the occupied Palestinian territories.
“If the future government of Israel, which will be established, proceeds to implement this plan, we will cancel all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made,” he said.
“We will reject the whole plan completely and completely,” Abbas said.
“It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means – no matter what the consequences – by fully engaging in the implementation of international law and in the fight against terrorism,” said the Palestinian Authority’s president, who made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, Israel’s former prime minister, was re-elected on Sept. 17 to form a government.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would declare the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank into Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, then led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised to hold a general election in the Palestinian territories during the UN General Assembly.
The last took place in 2006.
“When I return to the country, I will convene local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,” he said.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the UN, to exercise the powers of “full members of the UN and all its organs and institutions.”
The Palestinian leader ended his speech by calling on the international community to “force Israel to comply with the United Nations in all respects.”
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas's speech, saying the Palestinian leader "would rather focus at the United Nations on the Palestinian Authority's efforts against Israel than fight the calls for terrorism in the Authority under his leadership."
Danon, however, did not refer to Netanyahu’s announced annexation of the occupied Palestinian territories.
