PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry that create innovative solutions.
The National Center for Research and Development announced the results of the third edition of the GameINN program on Friday.
Among the almost 30 projects that supported the NCBR, the development of a virtual platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a real-world map with an application that allows users to transfer data; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills at work and professional development using the world of VR and AI; and an innovative simulation game management using the world of simulation.
The goal of the GameINN sector program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry on the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is PLN 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared research agenda of GameINN and the support for entrepreneurs already amounting to PLN 300 million under this sector program are an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev,” the statement reads.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
“Incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs who focus on innovation, such as R&D relief, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by the NCBR, drive the innovative activity of companies and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market,” said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jaros<0xC5><0x82>aw Gowin, quoted in the statement.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project co-financing, but also remains in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D relief in 2018 than a year earlier.
“The amount of deductible costs related to R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in more than PLN 300 million in savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN,” the Deputy Prime Minister emphasizes.
The Director of the NCBR, Wojciech Kamieniecki, Ph.D., recalls that in the two previous competitions, 78 innovative projects were awarded grants with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest in the III competition and the variety of applications submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competencies to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“We are particularly pleased that among the selected projects – as in the previous editions – there are projects for solutions not only for entertainment, but also related to industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding reaching up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of co-financing of about PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in funding.
Detailed information about the results of the III GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector program is implemented as part of the Intelligent Development Operational Program.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
