Iran's president says he rejected offer of talks with U.S., Donald Trump denies
Tehran did not enter into talks with the U.S. side during the UN General Assembly in New York, despite the U.S. offer to lift sanctions, Iranian President Hassan Rouhani said on Friday.
US President Donald Trump said it was the Iranian side that asked for the lifting of restrictions, to which he did not agree.
According to Iranian President Hassan Rouhani, the Americans proposed the lifting of all sanctions imposed on Tehran in exchange for negotiating a new international agreement.
It would regulate both Iran’s nuclear program and its ballistic missile program.
Rouhani: Iran will not engage in talks in an atmosphere of maximum pressure
The Iranian president said he did not agree to the talks because of the "toxic atmosphere".
He said he had met with U.S. diplomats because he had been persuaded by France, Germany and Britain.
However, he stressed that Iran will not engage in talks in an atmosphere of “maximum pressure”.
“Even if we want to negotiate with the Americans in the 5+1 format, no one can predict what the final result will be,” Rouhani said.
The day before, the Iranian leader said that he did not exclude talks with the United States, and European parties to the nuclear deal accused of favoring US sanctions on Iran.
He added that sanctions imposed on Iran after the US withdrawal from the nuclear deal “are a precondition that does not allow” for dialogue.
“If we can lift this precondition and if America lifts sanctions and maximum pressure, then of course we can talk to America,” he said.
He added that he did not rule out a meeting with U.S. President Donald Trump, even though he did not agree to such a conversation last week at the U.N. General Assembly.
Trump: “Iran asked, I said no”
Donald Trump tweeted that he had rejected the Iranian request.
“Iran wanted me to lift the sanctions imposed on them so that we could meet.
Of course I said no!” the US president tweeted.
Tension with nuclear agreement in the background
France, Germany and the United Kingdom are trying to ease tensions between Washington and Tehran in some form to save the 2015 agreement with Iran, to which they were signatories.
It stipulated that in exchange for the lifting of economic sanctions, Iran would abandon its nuclear weapons program and subject the nuclear sector to the control of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
Since the U.S. withdrawal from the deal in May 2015, other signatories have repeatedly confirmed that they want to keep the deal in place.
So far, nothing's come of it.
Washington is using the tactic of exerting maximum pressure on Iran, and the sanctions also include a full embargo on Iranian oil.
Tehran announced that if it does not receive permission to export raw materials, it will limit its obligations under the agreement every 60 days.
