These trees could disappear from Europe.
“42% of the tree species that make up Europe’s tree population are at risk,” warned the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in the Red Book of European Trees published on Friday.
At the top of the list are, among others, chestnuts and daisies.
IUCN, an organization based in Gland, Switzerland, is publishing a list of endangered European tree species for the first time.
It was drawn up by specialists who, based on research, came to the conclusion that out of 454 species of trees found in Europe (as well as in other places of the world), 42% are “highly endangered”.
Among the causes, the Red Book lists the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As for the typical European tree stand, according to IUCN experts, 58 percent of species are threatened, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the exploitation of the forest stand, accelerated urbanization, too intensive felling of trees, followed by forest fires and changes taking place in the European ecosystem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also strongly threatened.
“The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual extinction of European plant species and pose a danger in Europe to the extinction of important and undervalued varieties that form the basis of European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet,” Luc Bas, who heads IUCN’s European office, said in a statement.
