GUS: Life is getting better in Poland
According to the report on household budgets published by the Central Statistical Office on Friday, 44 percent of them assessed their financial situation as good or rather good.
The previous year this percentage was 37.2%, in 2016 33.5%, and earlier – since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households – never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their financial situation to be bad or rather bad in the previous year, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20% in 2009.
The material situation of households of self-employed persons is the best.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the second pole are households of pensioners, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also influenced by the number of children.
The worst is done by parents who raise their children alone, of which 32% declare a good or rather good financial situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8%.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), parents raising children alone and large families (with at least three children) assessed their worst financial situation.
Improving subjective assessments of the financial situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid growth of income, primarily from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation good is growing faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships there is no clear correlation between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are formulated by residents of the Opole voivodship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Then there are Lubuskie Provinces (47.7%), Silesian Provinces (47.6%), Mazowieckie Provinces (47.3%) and West Pomeranian Provinces (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opole the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94 percent of the national average in the previous year, and in Lubuski to 98 percent.
The residents of Mazowieckie (120% of the national average) and Silesian (104%) had the highest incomes.
On average, in Poland, disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1,693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjusting for the impact of price changes), it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, the result is quite low.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3%.
While revenue growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
Those per person amounted to PLN 1,187 in the last year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80%, and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
