Voting on the break in the proceedings of the Conservative Party conference
British MPs have voted against a three-day recess in the House of Commons for the Conservative Party’s annual programme conference, the government has asked.
There were 289 votes in favour and 306 against.
Normally, the House of Commons does not meet during party conferences, so that members do not have to resign either from participating in them or from parliamentary meetings.
However, the opposition parties decided that in such a crucial time as the last weeks before Britain’s planned departure from the European Union on October 31, the parliament should not interrupt the meeting.
The government's request for a break was supported by 289 deputies, against 306.
The two opposition parties are already out of the convention.
The refusal to agree to the break can be perceived as political revenge on Prime Minister Boris Johnson for his decision to suspend parliament for five weeks (on Tuesday, the decision was considered illegal and non-existent by the Supreme Court) and for not wanting to apologize for her after the judges’ ruling.
Following the ruling, the House of Commons resumed its session on Wednesday, with Johnson’s speech and the ensuing tumultuous debate being the most important event of the day.
Johnson accused the opposition of blocking Brexit and avoiding early elections.
“It is time to get Brexit done.
It must be done in order to respect the referendum result.
Brexit must come so that we can deal with an agreement on citizens’ priorities, on health care, on the cost of living.
“Brexit must be done so that we can unite this country,” Johnson said.
The Conservative Party conference is scheduled to start in Manchester next Sunday and run until Wednesday 2 October.
Conferences of the two main opposition groups – the Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats – have already taken place.
One of the reasons Johnson gave for the long suspension of parliament was party conferences.
