G<0xC3><0xB6>rlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for a review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an unusual offer prepared for newcomers German G<0xC3><0xB6>rlitz.
The measures are intended to help combat the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
G<0xC3><0xB6>rlitz is the easternmost city in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as The Guardian reports, the city is facing significant challenges.
G<0xC3><0xB6>rlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also experiencing a steady decline in population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which resulted in a 25% decline in the city's population.
In 2013, it reached 54,000 people.
To combat the depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been received for the programme.
Two thirds of them were made by residents of large cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the programme.
“When we applied, we thought that the program was to convince people to move to G<0xC3><0xB6>rlitz,” said one of the project participants.
“Now we feel that it doesn’t matter if we stay here after four weeks or not,” he added.
The city has 7,000 vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to get the opinions of the program participants.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revitalise smaller German cities.
“We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move, what their motivation was,” said program manager Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first of these was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa in Oklahoma.
